[{"phase":"FOUNDATION","items":[{"n":"01","title":"Discovering a Business Idea","subtitle":"Surface ideas aligned to your skills, passions, and real market gaps.","prompt":"I want to discover a viable business idea suited to me. Ask me a series of focused questions — one at a time — covering: my skills and background, problems I've personally noticed, industries I'm drawn to, how much time and money I can invest, and whether I prefer a product or service business. After my answers, suggest 5 concrete business ideas ranked by feasibility and explain the reasoning for each."},{"n":"02","title":"Mission & Vision Statement","subtitle":"Anchor every future decision with a clear purpose and direction.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. My target customer is: [DESCRIBE CUSTOMER]. The core problem I solve is: [DESCRIBE PROBLEM]. Help me craft a mission statement (why we exist, who we serve, what we do) and a vision statement (the future we are building toward). Provide 3 options for each — one practical and grounded, one aspirational, one values-led. Explain the difference between a mission and a vision, and suggest 5 core values that could underpin my business culture."},{"n":"03","title":"Problem Identification","subtitle":"Confirm a real, painful problem exists before you build anything.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA IN 1–2 SENTENCES]. Help me clearly define the core problem it solves. Answer: (1) Who exactly experiences this problem? (2) How frequently and how painfully? (3) How are they currently solving it, and why is that inadequate? (4) What evidence suggests this is widespread? Then give me 5 customer interview questions I can use to validate the problem firsthand."}]},{"phase":"RESEARCH","items":[{"n":"04","title":"Customer Research","subtitle":"Build a deep, detailed picture of your ideal customer.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. Create a detailed ideal customer persona covering: demographics, psychographics, daily routine, key frustrations and goals, where they spend time online and offline, how they currently discover and buy solutions like mine, and what would make them trust a new provider. Then give me 10 customer discovery interview questions to validate or refine this persona."},{"n":"05","title":"Market Research","subtitle":"Estimate the size, trends, and dynamics of your target market.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. Produce a market research summary covering: (1) estimated TAM, SAM, and SOM with reasoning, (2) key trends over the last 3–5 years, (3) what is driving growth or decline, (4) major customer segments, and (5) regulatory or external factors that could affect the market. Also suggest 5 free or low-cost sources I can use to research further."},{"n":"06","title":"Market Risk","subtitle":"Identify the market-level threats that could undermine your business.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. Analyse the market risks I face covering: (1) demand risk — could demand shrink or shift? (2) timing risk — am I too early or too late? (3) substitution risk — what could replace my solution? (4) concentration risk — am I dependent on one customer type or channel? (5) macro risks — economic, social, or technological forces that could disrupt the market. For each risk, rate likelihood (low/medium/high) and suggest a mitigation strategy."},{"n":"07","title":"Competitor Analysis","subtitle":"Map your competitive landscape and find where you can win.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. Identify my likely direct and indirect competitors. For each category describe: what they offer, pricing model, target customer, key strengths, and common weaknesses or customer complaints. Then identify the gaps in the market — where customers are underserved — and explain where a new entrant like me could realistically compete and differentiate."},{"n":"08","title":"Competitive Positioning","subtitle":"Define exactly where you sit in the market relative to every competitor.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. My main competitors are: [LIST 3–5]. Help me develop my competitive positioning. Identify the 2 most important dimensions customers use to evaluate options in my market (e.g. price vs quality, speed vs depth). Show me where competitors sit and where I should position myself. Then write a positioning statement: \"For [target customer] who [need], [my business] is the [category] that [key benefit], unlike [competitor] which [contrast].\" Suggest 3 alternative positioning angles I could test."}]},{"phase":"STRATEGY","items":[{"n":"09","title":"Value Proposition","subtitle":"Craft a compelling reason customers should choose you over anyone else.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. My target customer is: [DESCRIBE CUSTOMER]. My main competitors are: [LIST 2–3]. Using the Value Proposition Canvas, map: (1) my customer's jobs-to-be-done, pains, and gains, (2) how my offering is a pain reliever and gain creator, and (3) a concise one-sentence value proposition. Then write 3 alternative value proposition variations I could A/B test."},{"n":"10","title":"Business Model Design","subtitle":"Decide how your business creates, delivers, and captures value.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. Walk me through the Business Model Canvas for my business. For each of the 9 building blocks — key partners, key activities, key resources, value proposition, customer relationships, channels, customer segments, cost structure, and revenue streams — give me concrete examples relevant to my business. Then recommend the business model best suited to an early-stage, low-capital setup and explain why."},{"n":"11","title":"Branding Strategy","subtitle":"Build an identity and tone that connects authentically with your audience.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. My target customer is: [DESCRIBE CUSTOMER]. Help me develop a branding strategy covering: (1) brand positioning statement, (2) brand personality and tone of voice — give 5 descriptive words, (3) 5 business name ideas with reasoning, (4) visual direction — describe colours, style, and feel without designing anything, and (5) how my brand should make customers feel. Also explain the top 3 branding mistakes early-stage founders make."},{"n":"12","title":"Financial Planning","subtitle":"Map your costs, pricing, and the path to profitability.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. Help me build a basic financial plan covering: (1) estimated startup costs, (2) monthly operating costs once running, (3) pricing strategy and rationale, (4) break-even analysis — how many sales per month do I need to cover costs, and (5) a 12-month revenue projection across conservative, moderate, and optimistic scenarios. Explain all assumptions clearly."},{"n":"13","title":"Funding Options","subtitle":"Explore every realistic way to fund your business at each stage.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. My estimated startup cost is: [AMOUNT OR 'unknown']. My available personal savings are: [AMOUNT OR 'minimal']. For each funding option — bootstrapping, friends and family, small business loans, government grants, angel investors, crowdfunding, and accelerators — explain: what it is, whether it suits my stage, the pros and cons, and what I would need to qualify. Then recommend the best 1–2 options for my situation and why."}]},{"phase":"BUILD","items":[{"n":"14","title":"Legal Setup","subtitle":"Understand the structures, registrations, and protections you need from day one.","prompt":"I am starting a business in [YOUR COUNTRY / STATE]. My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. Guide me through legal setup covering: (1) pros and cons of different business structures and which suits me best, (2) how to register my business, (3) licences or permits likely required, (4) basic contracts I need from day one, (5) intellectual property considerations, and (6) the most common legal mistakes new founders make. Note: I will consult a lawyer for final decisions."},{"n":"15","title":"Compliance","subtitle":"Understand every rule, regulation, and standard your business must follow.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. I operate in: [YOUR COUNTRY / STATE / INDUSTRY]. Help me understand my compliance obligations covering: (1) industry-specific regulations or licences, (2) data protection and privacy laws if I collect customer data, (3) consumer protection laws, (4) tax registration and obligations, (5) employment law basics if I hire anyone, and (6) health and safety requirements if relevant. Then give me a compliance checklist I can work through before I launch."},{"n":"16","title":"Location Strategy","subtitle":"Decide where to operate — physical, remote, or hybrid — and what it requires.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. Help me think through my location strategy covering: (1) whether I need physical premises, a home base, or can operate fully remotely — and the trade-offs of each, (2) if physical: what to look for, estimated costs, and lease considerations, (3) if remote: tools, address requirements, and professional credibility, (4) zoning or local regulations to check, and (5) how location affects my customers' ability to find and access me."},{"n":"17","title":"Logistics","subtitle":"Plan how your product or service gets from you to your customer.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS — product or service]. Help me design my logistics and fulfilment process covering: (1) the end-to-end delivery journey from creation to customer receipt, (2) supplier or inventory management if applicable, (3) shipping or service delivery options and cost implications, (4) how to handle returns, refunds, or service failures, and (5) the logistics tools I should consider at an early stage. Flag the top 3 logistics risks and how to mitigate them."},{"n":"18","title":"Contracts","subtitle":"Identify every agreement you need and what each one must cover.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. I will work with: [CUSTOMERS / SUPPLIERS / FREELANCERS / PARTNERS — list what applies]. Identify every type of contract or written agreement I need from day one. For each — client agreements, supplier contracts, freelancer agreements, NDAs, terms and conditions, privacy policies — explain: what it covers, why it matters, and the key clauses to insist on. Also explain what happens if I operate without contracts and how to get started affordably. Note: I will have a lawyer review final versions."},{"n":"19","title":"Systems & Operations","subtitle":"Build the processes and tools that let your business run consistently.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. I will start with approximately [NUMBER] people. Help me design my operational foundation covering: (1) core business processes to document from day one, (2) a recommended affordable tools and software stack for operations, communications, and customer management, (3) how to ensure consistent customer fulfilment or service delivery, (4) quality control as I grow, and (5) a 30-day operational setup checklist."},{"n":"20","title":"Product / Service Development (MVP)","subtitle":"Design the smallest version you can launch to test your core idea.","prompt":"My business idea is: [DESCRIBE YOUR IDEA]. Help me plan my MVP — the smallest version I could offer that tests the core value with real customers. Then outline a phased roadmap: Phase 1 (MVP), Phase 2 (early growth features), Phase 3 (scale). For each phase list key deliverables, estimated timeframe, and the assumptions being tested. Also flag the top 3 development risks I should plan for."},{"n":"21","title":"Human Resource Strategy","subtitle":"Plan how to hire, onboard, and retain the right people as you grow.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. I currently plan to operate as: [SOLO / WITH CO-FOUNDER / SMALL TEAM OF X]. Help me build a people strategy covering: (1) which roles to hire first and in what order, (2) whether to use employees, freelancers, or contractors and the trade-offs, (3) how to write a compelling first job post or brief, (4) how to onboard someone without a formal HR department, (5) how to build a simple performance and feedback culture from day one, and (6) the most common people mistakes early-stage founders make."}]},{"phase":"LAUNCH","items":[{"n":"22","title":"Business Plan","subtitle":"Pull everything together into a complete, investor-ready document.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. My target market is: [DESCRIBE MARKET]. My business model is: [DESCRIBE HOW YOU MAKE MONEY]. Help me write a comprehensive business plan covering: (1) executive summary, (2) company overview and mission, (3) problem and solution, (4) target market and customer persona, (5) competitor analysis and positioning, (6) product or service description, (7) marketing and sales strategy, (8) operations plan, (9) team and key hires, (10) 12-month financial projections — revenue, costs, and break-even, and (11) funding requirements if applicable. Write each section clearly as if presenting to an investor or bank."},{"n":"23","title":"Marketing Strategy","subtitle":"Plan how you will reach, attract, and convert your ideal customers.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. My target customer is: [DESCRIBE CUSTOMER]. My monthly marketing budget is approximately: [STATE BUDGET OR 'very limited']. Build me a 90-day marketing strategy including: (1) the 2–3 channels best suited to my customer and why, (2) the messaging that will resonate, (3) a simple content calendar for month one, (4) 3 low-cost tactics I can start immediately, and (5) the key metrics I should track to know if it is working."},{"n":"24","title":"Sales Strategy","subtitle":"Design your end-to-end sales process from first contact to closed deal.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. My product/service price point is: [PRICE]. My typical customer is: [DESCRIBE CUSTOMER]. Design a sales strategy covering: (1) the most effective sales approach for my business type, (2) a step-by-step sales process from first contact to close, (3) how to handle the 3 most common objections, (4) a follow-up sequence for unconverted leads, and (5) how to set a realistic sales target for month one."},{"n":"25","title":"Media Kit","subtitle":"Create a professional kit to attract press, partnerships, and sponsors.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. My website is: [URL OR 'not yet live']. Help me build a media kit. Tell me what it should include, then draft content for each section: (1) business overview — one compelling paragraph, (2) mission and values, (3) product or service description, (4) target audience summary, (5) traction or milestones to date, (6) founder bio, (7) media coverage or testimonials placeholder, (8) partnership or sponsorship opportunities, and (9) contact information. Also advise on the best format and where to share it."},{"n":"26","title":"Launch Strategy","subtitle":"Plan a focused launch that generates real momentum from day one.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. I plan to launch in: [TIMEFRAME]. Build me a launch strategy covering: (1) pre-launch activities for the 4 weeks before launch to build anticipation, (2) a launch day plan — what to publish, post, and do, (3) post-launch follow-up for the first two weeks, (4) how to acquire my first 10 paying customers, (5) how to collect and act on early feedback, and (6) what success looks like at the end of week one and week four."}]},{"phase":"SCALE & EXIT","items":[{"n":"27","title":"Growth Strategy","subtitle":"Identify the levers that will scale your business sustainably.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. I have been operating for: [TIMEFRAME OR 'not yet launched']. My current monthly revenue is approximately: [AMOUNT OR 'pre-revenue']. Design a growth strategy for the next 12 months covering: (1) the 2–3 highest-leverage growth levers for my business type, (2) how to increase customer lifetime value, (3) referral and retention strategies, (4) when and how to expand my product or service offering, (5) the monthly metrics I should track, and (6) the biggest risks to growth and how to manage them."},{"n":"28","title":"Exit Strategy","subtitle":"Plan how you will eventually transition out — and what to protect now.","prompt":"My business is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS]. I am at stage: [EARLY / GROWING / ESTABLISHED]. Help me think through exit strategy options — acquisition, management buyout, merger, IPO, passing to family, lifestyle business (no exit), and wind-down — covering: what each involves, who it suits, what it requires to be viable, and the pros and cons. Then explain what decisions I should make now — even at an early stage — to keep options open and maximise future value.\nPro tip:\nCopy the outputs from earlier prompts (like your customer persona or value proposition) and paste them as context into later prompts. Each stage builds on the last."}]}]